{{See|gît}}
==English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /gɪt/
===Etymology ===
From before 1300 a get was what had been begotten, a child or offspring. But by about 1500 it had started to be used in [[w:Scotland|Scotland]] and northern [[w:England|England]] in the sense of misbegotten, a bastard; from there it became a general term of abuse for a fool or idiot. By about 1700 get seems to have lapsed into slang or dialect, only to reappear in the wider language in the 1940s with a different spelling and lacking the associations with illegitimacy. [[w:James Joyce|James Joyce]] uses the older spelling (and meaning) in [[w:Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]] in 1922: “The bloody thicklugged sons of whores’ gets!” These days, it’s a widely known and used term of abuse in Britain for somebody regarded as totally worthless or useless, most commonly appearing in cries of frustration such as “that stupid git, now look what he’s done!”.

